                <li>
                  Payoff date, interest savings and time saved with extra
                  payments
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>The mortgage payment formula</h3>
              <p>
                The base principal-and-interest payment for a fixed-rate
                mortgage is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="mb-1">
                  <strong>Monthly payment (principal &amp; interest):</strong>
                </p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <code>P</code> = loan amount (home price − down payment)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <code>r</code> = monthly interest rate (annual rate ÷ 12 ÷
                    100)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <code>n</code> = total number of payments (years × 12)
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p>Then the monthly payment is:</p>
                <p>\\( M = P \cdot \dfrac{r(1+r)^n}{(1+r)^n - 1} \\)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator computes this base payment, then adds your
                estimated property taxes, insurance, PMI and HOA dues to show
                your total monthly housing cost.
              </p>
              <p>
                For a plain‑language overview of mortgage terms, escrow, and
                monthly payment components, see the Consumer Financial
                Protection Bureau (CFPB) mortgage education materials:
                <a
                  href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/consumer-tools/mortgages/"
                  class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener"
                  >CFPB: Mortgages</a
                >.
              </p>

              <h3>What is included in your monthly mortgage payment?</h3>
              <p>
                Most homeowners pay more than just principal and interest each
                month. Lenders often collect these items in an escrow account:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Principal:</strong> The portion of your payment that
                  reduces your loan balance.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Interest:</strong> The cost of borrowing money from
                  the lender.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Property taxes:</strong> Annual property taxes divided
                  by 12.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Homeowners insurance:</strong> Annual premium divided
                  by 12.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>PMI:</strong> Required on many conventional loans when
                  your down payment is under 20%.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>HOA dues:</strong> Monthly fees for condos or
                  communities with a homeowners association.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>How PMI is estimated</h3>
              <p>
                PMI is typically charged as a percentage of your loan amount per
                year (for example 0.5%–1.5%). This calculator:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Checks whether your down payment is below 20% of the home
                  price.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If so, applies your chosen PMI rate to the current loan
                  balance.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Shows the monthly PMI cost and includes it in your total
                  payment.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                In reality, PMI may drop off once your loan-to-value (LTV)
                reaches 80% and you meet lender requirements. For background on
                PMI and LTV thresholds, see the CFPB explanation:
                <a
                  href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/ask-cfpb/what-is-private-mortgage-insurance-pmi-en-122/"
                  class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener"
                  >CFPB: What is PMI?</a
                >. For simplicity, this tool assumes PMI continues for the full
                term, which slightly overestimates long‑term costs and keeps the
                math transparent.
              </p>

              <h3>Extra payments and interest savings</h3>
              <p>
                Extra payments applied to principal reduce your balance faster,
                which:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Shortens your payoff time.</li>
                <li>Cuts total interest paid over the life of the loan.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>The calculator lets you add:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Extra monthly payments</strong> (for example rounding
                  up your payment).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Extra annual payments</strong> (for example a yearly
                  bonus).
                </li>
                <li><strong>One-time lump sum</strong> in the first month.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                It then compares the original schedule (no extras) to the new
                schedule and shows:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>New payoff date.</li>
                <li>Time saved (months and years).</li>
                <li>Interest saved.</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How to use the mortgage payment calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter the home price.</strong> Use the purchase price
                  or an estimated value.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Set your down payment.</strong> You can type either a
                  dollar amount or a percentage; the other field updates
                  automatically.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choose the loan term.</strong> Drag the slider or
                  click a preset (15, 20, 30 years).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Adjust the interest rate.</strong> Use your quoted
                  rate or a current market estimate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Estimate property taxes and insurance.</strong> If you
                  are unsure, start with 1%–1.5% for taxes and $800–$2,000 per
                  year for insurance depending on your area.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Decide whether to include PMI.</strong> Leave it on if
                  your down payment is under 20%.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Add HOA dues and extra payments</strong> if they apply
                  to you.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Review the summary box</strong> to see your total
                  monthly payment and payoff details.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Scroll the amortization table</strong> to see how each
                  payment is split between principal and interest.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Government guidance you can use</h2>
              <p>
                These official resources help you validate inputs and
                understand how lenders evaluate mortgages:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Consumer finance basics:</strong>
                  <a
                    href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/consumer-tools/mortgages/"
                    class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener"
                    >CFPB mortgage tools and guides</a
