              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Is my mortgage payment fixed for the entire term?</h3>
              <p>
                With a fixed-rate mortgage, your principal and interest payment
                stays the same for the life of the loan. However, your total
                monthly payment can still change if property taxes, insurance
                premiums or HOA dues go up or down. Adjustable-rate mortgages
                (ARMs) can also change when the interest rate resets.
              </p>

              <h3>How much house can I afford?</h3>
              <p>
                Lenders often look for a <strong>front-end DTI</strong> (housing
                costs ÷ gross monthly income) under about 28% and a
                <strong>back-end DTI</strong> (all debts ÷ income) under about
                36%–43%, depending on the loan program. Use this calculator
                together with a debt-to-income ratio tool to see how different
                home prices and down payments affect affordability.
              </p>

              <h3>What is the difference between principal and interest?</h3>
              <p>
                Principal is the amount you borrowed. Interest is the fee the
                lender charges for using their money. Early in your mortgage,
                most of your payment goes toward interest; over time, more goes
                toward principal. The amortization schedule in this calculator
                makes that shift easy to see.
              </p>

              <h3>Should I pay extra on my mortgage?</h3>
              <p>Paying extra can be a good idea if:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>You have an adequate emergency fund.</li>
                <li>
                  You have paid off higher-interest debt (like credit cards).
                </li>
                <li>
                  You plan to stay in the home long enough to benefit from the
                  interest savings.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Use the extra payment fields to see exactly how much time and
                interest you could save.
              </p>

              <h3>Does this calculator include closing costs?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This tool focuses on your ongoing monthly payment and
                amortization schedule. Closing costs are typically 2%–5% of the
                purchase price and are paid upfront at closing. Some buyers
                choose to roll certain costs into the loan, which would increase
                the loan amount and monthly payment.
              </p>
              <p>
                The CFPB explains common closing cost categories and how they
                appear on the Loan Estimate:
                <a
                  href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/ask-cfpb/what-are-closing-costs-and-how-much-are-they-en-136/"
                  class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener"
                  >CFPB closing costs overview</a
                >.
              </p>

              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-6">
                This calculator is for educational purposes only and does not
                constitute financial or lending advice. Actual mortgage terms,
                costs and eligibility depend on your lender and local
                regulations.
              </p>
